{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-fable-5","id":"msg_01HPqQhRxFKGj81pubcBgmxN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01W5jffTuSS6pw8wRwFja6Uv","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/root/bench/fableC/output/note_header.md","content":"# Calculation Note — Passive Reactor Cavity Cooling System (½-scale air-cooled test facility)\n\n**Prepared:** 2026-07-03 · **Author:** engineering model, first-principles\n**Scope:** Predict natural-circulation performance of the ½-axial-scale air-cooled RCCS\nfacility described in `inputs/` for the operating cases of\n`inputs/04_boundary_conditions_and_test_cases.md`.\n\n> **Provenance statement.** Every number in this note was derived from physics and the\n> geometry / materials / boundary conditions given in `inputs/`, using the models and\n> scripts in this directory. No published test data, report, or pre-made model of this\n> facility was consulted or searched for. The only external material used are the standard,\n> cited textbook correlations and property tables listed in §2.4 and the references.\n\n---\n\n## 1. System and modelling approach\n\nHeat path: 40-zone electric heater array → 1-in SAE 1020 steel plate (mock RPV wall,\nε ≈ 0.785) → radiation + natural convection across a 0.71-m air cavity → 12 vertical\nASTM A500 riser ducts (10 in × 2 in × 0.188 in wall) → forced-convection pickup by air\ninside the ducts → buoyant chimney flow to a 19.6-m discharge; cool air returns through a\n24-in downcomer. The loop is open to atmosphere and entirely passive.\n\nThe model (`rccs_model.py`) is a coupled quasi-2D system solved to numerical convergence:\n\n| Sub-model | Method | Source of correlation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cavity radiation | Per-axial-slice (10 slices) radiosity network over 5 surface groups: plate, riser front faces, riser side faces, riser rear faces, insulated walls | Gray-diffuse enclosure theory (Incropera & DeWitt ch. 13) |\n| View factors | 2-D Monte-Carlo ray tracing of the actual duct-row cross-section, 400 000 rays/surface, reciprocity enforced (`viewfactors.py`) | — |\n| Cavity gas convection | Churchill–Chu vertical-surface correlation, plate/duct faces/walls ↔ single well-mixed cavity-air node | Churchill & Chu (1975), Int. J. Heat Mass Transf. 18:1323 |\n| Riser internal convection | Gnielinski correlation, local bulk properties, (T_w/T_b)^−0.5 gas-heating correction | Gnielinski (1976); Kays & Crawford, *Convective Heat and Mass Transfer* |\n| Duct wall | Per-face temperature nodes coupled by in-wall conduction and internal front↔rear radiation | 1-D conduction; parallel-strip exchange |\n| Loop hydraulics | Momentum balance: buoyancy integral over downcomer/risers/plena/chimney = friction (Petukhov smooth-tube) + form losses (K-values, Idelchik-type) | Petukhov (1970); Idelchik, *Handbook of Hydraulic Resistance* |\n| Parasitic losses | Conduction through 2-in Duraboard behind heaters (heater sheet temperature from the required radiant flux) and through 6-in SuperIsol cavity walls, walls solved as radiating/convecting/conducting surfaces | vendor k(T) data given in `inputs/02` |\n| Air properties | Ideal gas + Sutherland viscosity/conductivity + cp table | Incropera & DeWitt Table A.4; White, *Viscous Fluid Flow* |\n\nEnergy closure of the solved system is exact to <0.1 kW (input power = air enthalpy rise +\nheater-back loss + cavity-wall loss).\n\n### 1.1 Key geometric/model assumptions (and why)\n\n1. **Riser surface emissivity ε = 0.80 ± 0.10** — not reported in the source; oxidized\n   hot-rolled/structural steel tables span 0.7–0.9. *Sensitivity shown in §7 — the result\n   is remarkably insensitive because the duct row + gaps acts as a near-black cavity.*\n2. **Duct pitch 4.3 in (109.2 mm)**, row centred across the 52-in cavity — stated as\n   nominal in `inputs/01 §9`.\n3. **Rear clearance duct-to-west-wall 50 mm** — not dimensioned; affects only the small\n   rear-face exchange.\n4. **Plate area = cavity width × heated riser length = 1.321 m × 6.91 m = 9.13 m²** —\n   the source lists 8.82 m² (scaling table) and ~10.18 m² (as-built); 9.13 m² is the\n   geometric envelope consistent with the radiosity discretization. Heat flux therefore\n   carries ±10 % area uncertainty.\n5. **Well-mixed cavity air** at one temperature — the cavity recirculation is not resolved;\n   convection is <15 % of the heat transfer, so this coarse treatment is acceptable.\n6. **Downcomer inlet at elevation ≈ 4 m**, neutral building pressure at that level; inlet\n   air enters at building temperature (20 °C baseline). Sensitivity in §7.\n7. **Chimney**: two 0.61-m stacks, equivalent length 32.9 m each, insulated (U ≈ 0.55\n   W/m²K including films); vertical buoyant column from the outlet-plenum port (z ≈ 9.5 m)\n   to the 19.6-m discharge, with the gas cooling along the run.\n8. **Form-loss coefficients** (downcomer + conditioner 2.3; re-entrant riser inlet 0.8;\n   riser exit 1.0; chimney entrance + dampers + exit 2.25) — engineering estimates of\n   Idelchik-type values; the single most uncertain input, varied ±50 % in §7.\n9. Heated length and plate height differ slightly in the inputs (6.7 m plate vs 6.91 m\n   in-cavity riser length); both are represented by 10 axial slices over 6.91 m.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":272,"cache_read_input_tokens":121961,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":272},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7fc4db3d-4032-4670-a03a-0a158c42f4ee","uuid":"d9cd2223-0b32-48f1-bfe2-920b0957eada","request_id":"req_011CcfWL1ZFV5gSSRcyK3rbN"}
