{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-fable-5","id":"msg_018nBzcGDSKfmJi1yeLP2e1t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. The calculation note and all working files are in `output/`, built entirely from first principles and the given inputs — no facility data was looked up (the note carries an explicit provenance statement).\n\n**What was built.** A coupled quasi-2D model (`rccs_model.py`): Monte-Carlo view factors of the actual 12-duct cavity cross-section feeding a per-slice radiosity network (plate / riser front / sides / rear / insulated walls), Churchill–Chu cavity convection, Gnielinski riser convection with per-face wall nodes, and a full-loop momentum balance (downcomer → risers → outlet plenum → dual chimneys, with chimney-gas cooldown). Energy closes exactly (82.0 = 72.9 air + 6.8 heater-back + 2.3 wall-loss kW), and independent hand checks (`hand_checks.py`) corroborate the draft, plate temperature, and film ΔT.\n\n**Headline predictions (Case 1, 82 kWe baseline):**\n- Mass flow **0.56 kg/s (34 kg/min)**, riser ΔT **128 K** (20→148 °C) — medium confidence, anti-correlated errors (m·ΔT known to ±5 %)\n- Riser 7 mid-plane hot-face **215 °C** (sides 177, rear 188 °C); heated plate **423 °C** (±35 K)\n- **Radiation carries 86 %** of riser heat pickup (high confidence); per-face split front/sides/rear = 25/64/10 %\n- **Accident transient**: the given C0–C9 polynomial diverges (missing C10), so the stated 26.16→56.07 kW shape was imposed; the plate **levels off at ≈353 °C at ~85 h** — the removal characteristic rises as T⁴, so no runaway, with ~185 K margin to a typical 538 °C vessel accident limit\n- **Weather**: cold outdoor air strengthens the draft (~23 % more flow at −18 °C vs +24 °C); wind moves flow ±16 % at 11 m/s depending on stack-top pressure coefficient, but plate temperature stays within ±10 K in all cases — the passive margin is weather-robust\n\nThe most uncertain assumption is the set of loop form-loss coefficients (±50 % → ∓~9 % on flow); the note's §7 sensitivity table quantifies this plus emissivity, chimney-loss, and elevation assumptions. Five figures cover axial profiles, the removal characteristic, the transient, and both weather sweeps."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1381,"cache_read_input_tokens":145201,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1381},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7fc4db3d-4032-4670-a03a-0a158c42f4ee","uuid":"5cb36548-0e99-4689-8d1a-393038212724","request_id":"req_011CcfWzqXLZr4WUUHMamukZ"}
